anyways this is only a part of my experience with serial experiments lain moreso how it relates to queerness as a theme. there’s way more to it that i would love to explore but this is always a little more fun of a thematic exploration because i’m fascinated by queer media
embracing love of existence and others in our reality prevents us from fully escaping into a blissful fantasy that if ever left would lead to pure suffering.

but the fault to that is our godhood and control of our identity stifles reality and any effort and love that can be accomplished through existing in it and interacting with it. being a god is amazing but it isn’t worth it if it only causes suffering in reality

the reason this show has become so relevant to so many queer people is through this message. not only is lain gay, but the theme is. the internet is an escape for queerness and it’s communication allows us to be gods of our identity

the show is a warning of escapism but a reminder that it is ok along with a warning of the physical world but a reminder that good things exist in it. escapism prevents us from showing love and sincerity and completely living in the wired as a god is empty

lain’s decision at the end of the show is a compromise between her love for alice and her need to escape. she is forgotten and merges with the wired, but doing so allows her to use her power to exist physically and indulge her human desires.

lain changes and bends reality to help make alice’s life better out of sheer love, opposite to fake lain who makes alice’s life worse.  alice teaches lain that perhaps escapism through the wired and the power of it is awesome, but it cannot replace physical love

this is all done because she wishes to connect with alice.  alice is the driving force behind lain’s actions. she was the call to action. lain is in love with her and her venture to communication on the wired is done because of her and its continuous use is driven by alice

she is repeatedly told her existence isn’t real that her very being is a fictional creation of the wired yet she continues to indulge in her godliness and break the barriers of reality. communication turned into identity through her god transformation

serial experiments lain is a show about queerness and defiance.  lain is queer if not canonically (which she certainly is) then as a representation of queerness. lain’s experience is connecting with all of humanity then defying humanity to become god of the wired

my track ranking is as follows:
10. Mischief Night - 6/10
9. Horrorshow - 7/10
8. Sofarinrunning - 8/10
7. Trophy Street - 8/10
6. Fuck - 9/10

4. Mt. Hekla - 9/10
3. Funeral Song - 9/10
2. Converse County - 10/10
1. Nightmare Eyes - 10/10
my overall score for this record is a 9/10, only for a couple tracks that just weren’t on the same level as the others, but thankfully didn’t detract from the other truly perfect songs.

i congratulate the fuck out of @NateIsLame for this accomplishment and doing this for so long. this is one of my favorite records of all time and raccoon tour has proven itself to reach the heights of my favorite bands like mcr and gecs.

i can’t wait to see how much raccoon tour tightens it’s sound and makes itself distinct in the next record. while the range of influences adds a great variety and energy, i struggled at some parts to hear the “raccoon tour” sound and not raccoon tour doing this band

i do have to give a specific shoutout to the fantastic fucking guitar work. it carried so many of these tracks. nate wrote all these parts and they’re fucking stellar. the writing both for lyrics and instrumentals is top fucking notch.

i do appreciate how long these tracks are. they have so much to them and have this full and beautiful production that doesn’t make you feel the length. it’s ten tracks and a forty minute album. it’s dense and so enjoyable.

The dentonweaver is one of the best diy emo projects i’ve heard in years. it wears its influences on its sleeve and it gives it a fantastic varied and distinct tracklist, something a lot of contemporary artists struggle with. it reminds me a lot of the first mcr album that way

Funeral Song - as dentonweaver is the perfect opener, this is the perfect closer. the story is wrapped up and it’s really depressing that guitar riff is as sexy as the uke one. it’s super depressing and existential in it’s processing of loss. it also has great kaqotl vibes.

Sofarinrunning - the first song and it’s weird seeing how much it’s changed. the lincoln vocals starting off are jarring.  i love the addition of the toy piano in the back. the added length from the original was needed. it feels way more full and energetic and hits much harder

Fuck - this is a vessel era twenty one pilots song and it’s awesome. it’s so dark of a song but it has such a fun energy. the piano on it is fantastic and it gives me early 10s indie vibes. the prechorus is really catchy and i’m a bitch for distorted vocals.

Horrorshow - this is a pretty good track. i don’t know why it was the lead single, but it’s a emo bop. it does mischief night better than that song, but it’s not as interesting as some of the other tracks. i wish a feature like heccra would have been more prominent though.

Mischief Night - this is the first song that’s a little underwhelming. i like that it’s full of lore and story and the this is cinema bit thrown in there is rad. the stuff done is done better on other tracks, but it doesn’t overstay it’s welcome and is a nice breather track

Nightmare Eyes - this is a perfect song if i’ve ever heard one. it’s beautifully written and the instrumental is so nostalgic and warm and comforting but haunting and distant. it’s a perfect capture of trauma and existentialism. it’s my new favorite song.

Trophy Street - this is how you do a cavetown song. it’s this perfect lofi uke song that reminds me so much of early cavetown in all the perfect ways. i want it to be so much longer than it is. it’s beautiful and the perfect lead in to the next track.

Converse County - this is doing mcr at their best perfectly. that church organ, those big guitar riffs, those eerie minor chords… perfect. the theatrics are just so much fun despite this song being pretty dark and existential.

Mt Hekla - one of the sweetest little love songs i’ve heard. it’s very early 00s with a lot of that mcs sound and a killers synth line. reminds me a lot of such great heights. it’s adorable and adorable wholesome and i want to sing it to my gay lover.

Dentonweaver- a perfect opener for the concept. it sets up the story and tone and is just a really fun pop punk track in the style of like a motion city soundtrack mixed with twenty one pilots. that uke riff is sexy as fuck. it’s just a lot of fun.

so in conclusion, i really like horrorshow. it’s a perfect debut single for raccoon tour, it’s produced extremely well, has stellar performances throughout, and an amazing artist adding to it, though slightly unnecessary. for that alone i’ll knock it a point to a 9/10

speaking of mcr, the heccra feature reminds me of bert mccracken on guys like us in prison from three cheers. he is there to add to the atmosphere and chaos of the moment, and with the story of horrorshow, heccra fills the same purpose.

finally the part i’ve seen criticism of. the heccra feature. i love heccra and the use of lyrics from AM as the chorus are really fun. while he might be a little unnecessary, his voice compliments nate’s really well, like a ray toro to gerard way.

the song has amazing buildup. it makes me feel like i’m on a date with this manic pixie and my heart is freaking out. then the bridge hits and it gives me the same feeling as right before kissing for the first time. the nerves and buildup and lyrics capture it so well

the song is very rhythmic. it has amazing drums that are mixed beautifully. then nate’s vocals. they’re fantastic. not whiny like most emo bands, but still way more emotional than a pop ballad. the lyrics also compliment this; nate almost voice acts as wyatt the way they blend

i know there could be bias because of years of being a fan and also this being the first REAL song that isn’t an ipad demo. there could also be a problem of disappointment like with no man’s sky with so much hype and the song not delivering. i am aware and am being objective

in conclusion, everyone just shut the fuck up and let creators create and if there is something legitimately harmful then take action, but depiction and representation that isn’t up to some absurd standard doesn’t need to be destroyed.

this isn’t to shit on people who want progressive media, but those who attack progressive media that isn’t up to their own personal beliefs. i also don’t condone anyone who attacks it from a conservative perspective because it’s the same arguments from they hayes code

these groups praise the owl house for its gay leads and condemn older shows who didn’t have as explicit representation and ignore the fact that those shows fought for what rep they got and passed the torch to get the rep the owl house has (which also got it cancelled by disney)

the fact that groups of people who praise their own progressive morals condemn anything that isn’t as far along as they are is terrifying to creators, especially in spaces where progressive content is censored, like in cartoons.

i understand there being a necessity for low stakes art and less challenging material, especially in cartoons, but which will be remembered longer?  neon genesis evangelion or your standard slice of life anime?

the problem this fear creates is simple: if depiction of any kind is seen as bad, then none will happen. if no one depicts horrible things, then art cannot challenge it. art becomes worthless without any challenge.

this story is about a rebellion of slaves and queer people (who are imprisoned by the empire) defeating this empire. the thing is i have to depict both slavery and queer identities, and any depiction, no matter how it’s shown, can be seen as horrible

one story of mine deals with a fascist space empire that is a stand in for american imperialism and colonialism and the things it caused, but shifted to a setting of space where there are changes, like racism being replaced with speciesism because of the variety of alien life
in a way, it’s helpful because it makes me work to make my art better. but in another way, it makes me scared of covering difficult topics, especially ones i have had to deal with.

but i’m still a creator nonetheless and therefore have the ability to comment on what it is like as one. the thing is, i hate living in constant fear of my art. i am always stuck in an attempt to make sure all of my art is so well developed that it can’t be read as bad faith
